<div id="stitle" style="display:none;">Notebook Entry</div>
<dl id="n05034e"> <dt class="nbunit"><a name="n05" href="#n05034e">N05 (VI.B.2)</a>:  <a href="../../ff/fnbs/n05all.htm#n05034e"> 34(e)</a></dt> <dd> <blockquote> <font color="green">[i]</font> monk close to the usurper / rejoiced wonderfully</blockquote> <dd class="well"> <blockquote class="sources">Maximus asked him again and again to the Imperial table, but in vain; he declined alleging that he could not partake in the hospitality of one who had deprived one Emperor of his dominions and another of his life. &hellip; at length overcome by his arguments or his prayers, <mark>Martin came to supper, the Emperor rejoicing wonderfully</mark> that he had prevailed with him. &hellip; The day of entertainment was made quite a gala day: the first personages about the Court were invited; the monk, Martin, was placed on a couch close to the usurper, and near him his attendant presbyter, seated between the brother and uncle of Maximus. <small> Margaret Maitland, <a name="MMLL" href="../../ff/fdra/fdex.htm#MMLL"><cite title="source">Life and Legends of St. Martin of Tours (316-397)</cite></a> (1908) 58-60</small></blockquote> </dd></dl>
